,"Vestibulospinal","Anterior corticospinal","Rubrospinal","Lateral corticospinal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily responsible for maintaining balance and posture by modulating anti-gravity reflexes. It receives input from the vestibular nuclei and projects to spinal motor neurons that control axial and proximal limb muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other tracts have different primary functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReticulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E - Modulates muscle tone and autonomic functions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E - Controls axial and proximal limb movements\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubrospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E - Facilitates flexor muscle activity in upper limbs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E - Controls fine voluntary movements, especially of the distal limbs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibulospinal system works in concert with other motor pathways to maintain balance and make automatic postural adjustments during movement. It is particularly important for maintaining upright posture against gravity and stabilising gaze during head movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vestibulospinal tract maintains balance and posture by modulating extensor muscle tone and anti-gravity reflexes.","The vestibulospinal tract receives input from the vestibular nuclei and projects to spinal motor neurons controlling axial and proximal limb muscles.","The vestibulospinal system works with other descending motor pathways to coordinate automatic postural adjustments during movement."],